# Installation
## Set up AC conda environment by running the following commands on Kestrel and on Vermillion
conda env create -f environment.yaml
conda activate AC_hero
pip install -e .

# Running in Python
## These are the various hero controllers available:
 1. controller_noAC.py manually adds several tasks to the Hero queue without using AC
 2. controller_manual.py manually adds several tasks to the Hero queue without using AC HeroDataset
 3. controller_offline_training.py add tasks to the Hero queue using manual, random, and bayesian optimization methods.
 4. controller_offline_inference.py read a trained surrogate from a file and use it in an offline manner (no retraining) for inference.
 5. controller_online_inference.py read a trained surrogate from a file and use it in an online manner, collecting new training data if the variance exceeds a threshold.

## To run any of these controllers, open a terminal on Kestrel or Vermillion and run the following commands:
cd examples/hero_2clusters
module load conda
conda activate AC_hero
python <controller_name>.py # replace <controller_name> with the actual file name

## A queue manager checks the hero queue and submits corresponding slurm jobs on a cluster where the manager is running. 
## All of the controllers listed above (except for the offline_inference controller) add tasks to the hero queue.
## So you will need to have at least one manager running for these controllers otherwise, the controller's tasks will never be completed.
## For instance, we suggest running a queue manager on a login node of Kestrel and one on a login node of Vermillion. This will queue jobs on both clusters and unqueue them if they begin to execute on the other machine. 
## Note that this will likely involve opening three terminals, one to run the controller on either machine and one additional on each machine to run the managers.
## Run the following commands in a terminal on both Kestrel and Vermillion:
cd examples/hero_2clusters
module load conda
conda activate AC_hero
python manager.py

# Running in C++
## Instead of running the .py controllers, it is possible to run the .cpp counterpart instead using the following steps:

~~~{.bash}
module load conda
conda activate AC_hero
~~~

Export library path
~~~{.bash}
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:~/.conda-envs/AC_hero/lib
~~~
Assuming that this is the path where `libpython3.11.so` is located

Compile c++ code
~~~{.bash}
g++ controller_offline_inference.cpp -o controller_offline_inference -L ~/.conda-envs/AC_hero/lib -lpython3.11 -I ~/.conda-envs/AC_hero/include/python3.11
~~~
Assuming `libpython3.XX.so` can be found at the library path
And Assuming `Python.h` can be found at the include path

Note: C++ program loads and executes the Python file at runtime, not during compilation. So you can change the python file after compilation.
